segments.text: on top of the Ag building.
Oh, it was just so tremendous.
Do you remember going to Muster when you were a student?
The only time I remember going to Muster was when we mustered with Corregidor in 1942.
You mean?
Corregidor.
You mean when they came back after the war was over?
No, sir.
While they were on Corregidor.
Describe that one.
Oh, that was, we all went down.
I was standing in front of the Ag building and they had speakers all over the place and

General Moore, who was our commandant, got on the air, and he says how happy he was to address the Corps and A&M, and they're all doing fine and well, and that the Aggies, I think he said there were about 22 Aggies there, and they asked if any of the
A&M graduates who were there on Corregidor if they had something to say and they would typical, hey Aggies, old Army, how you doing?
We didn't say howdy then.
It was old Army.
But it was very solemn.
Was there anyone on Corregidor that you had known personally?
Carl Pipkin.
Carl Pipkin?
Pipkin.
P-I-P-K-I-N.
Yes, sir.
He was there.
And, of course, I knew Colonel Moore.
Now, had he been the commandant here before he left?
Left.
He was a colonel.
And he left and went to Pacific and became a general.
But other than that, I can't recall any other names.
Aggies that I knew, probably if I heard the names I would tell you yes or no that I knew.
So you went to Yale practice regularly, Silver Taps, that muster you remember.
What were some other events, serious or otherwise, that you and almost everybody felt you ought to go to?
Everybody went to the football games.
Everybody went to the basketball games.
Deware Gym held, I think the seating capacity was around 4,500.
There were 7,000 of us here.
I think every dadgum 7,000 cadet was in that Deware Gym.
We helped make the movie, you know.
We've never been late.
We've never been late.
Oh, describe that.
Well, that was kind of a mass thing.
I never individually, as handsome and good looking as I was, was never asked to pardon it.
But it was all, it was good.
We participated in it.
How long were the, how long was that going on?
It went on for several months.
Really?
Yeah, and they came into the mess hall and they took
camera shots of us waiting tables and that was at Sabisa.
And then we had to get down in front of the Y and have Yale practice where they took shots of that and they caught us marching and
So that was over a period of several weeks or months or so.
So it wasn't all done in a period of two or three days.
Did you all get to see all those celebrities, Robert Mitchell?
Oh, yeah.
They'd shake hands with us and holler at us.
And Gwen.
Where did they live?
Were they at the Aggieland?
I think they were at the Aggieland Inn.
Right.
Yeah.
And then do you remember when you saw the movie first?
Yeah, what was that like?
I can't believe that's A&M.
They made it look better?
They sure did.
Glamorized it.
But that was quite something.
And it was nice for A&M.
Did anybody, did any student or group of students attempt any kind of pranks or good bull while they were trying to film it?
No, there was no demonstration of any kind.
Everybody was very cooperative because they knew that it would help the image of the university.
Now, as the war is going on,
You and your buddies at night, did you all talk about the progress?
We really didn't.
We were all busy studying.
We didn't talk too much about it.
Did you think about dropping out of school?
No.
And volunteering?
You were going to get your degree?
I was going to get my degree before I was called up to service.
Did you ever have any real financial problem where you had to turn to somebody to really help you out of a jam?
Well, I know Papa went down to the bank and hocked himself up high.
And my brother would send a few step-ins to us.
But see, that was payback for me.
I stayed out two years.
and to help them while they were in college and then Papa while he was at home.
I can't recall any anxieties.
You're number three of your brothers who came to A&M.
I was number three of the four of us.
Oh, okay.
And there are five brothers?
No, four brothers and one sister.
Oh, okay.
One sister, my youngest sister.
And I was number three.
Okay, you were number three.
Yeah.
How did you get a date as a student?
As a student?
We never had any dates here.
I had to invite them.
I invited one young lady from Bay City.
I'd met her when I worked there one summer, one winter.
And I liked her and I invited her to come up.
She brought her mother to be well chaperoned.
And it was the artillery ball.
And it was nice.
But dates, we would write TSCW and say we got this infantry ball or whatever ball we had.
How many girls could come and they would write back and say we've got 60, 70, 100 girls.
So we would vacate a dormitory and let them stay there.
And how did you get a date from one of those girls?
Just by picking the name.
Is that right?
That's all, yeah.
And sometimes did end up with a dull girl?
Well, sometimes they would end up with a dull cadet.
I'll tell you one experience I had in my freshman year, one of my seniors,
Slim Neely, he had made arrangements with a date with a girl from TSCW.
And he said, now Fish Kokonos, I want you to go down there and you ask for Betty, I forget her name, and if she's good looking you come back and tell me.
She's not good looking.
Tell her I had to leave this weekend and I wouldn't be here."
So I went down there.
A couple of us went down there.
They had the same assignment.
And we decided if we were good looking, we were going to come back and say, oh man, it was horrible.
And then we'd go have a date with them.
Because they didn't care.
They just had a date with a cadet.
So we had a lot of fun with that.
Describe one of the big dances, say the artillery dance.
Sabisa Hall, really nice.
Little Jack Little was the orchestra and they played real good music and we danced and just had real good fun.
Did you all decorate Sabisa?
We did.
The cadets did.
I don't know who did.
But it was decorated?
I don't think.
A couple of times it might have been.
And how did the Aggies conduct themselves at a dance?
I don't recall any bad instance of anything at a dance.
And how were the girls treated?
Oh, like ladies, really were.
I don't recall anything that ever happened to a girl that we invited down.
All right now when the dance was over, would they ever go anywhere after the
No, because it was a curfew and we had to get them back and a lot of us didn't have cars to go anywhere.
And we'd walk around the campus and explain to the girls this is ag, this is the wine, this is law and prayer, and this is Mitchell Hall and Bazell and we'd walk around the campus.
Where did, if anybody wanted to get a drink then, where did they go?
You mean alcohol?
You know, I really don't know because I really didn't drink, didn't smoke, but we had Uncle Ed Hard Liquor.
It was a nice club that people went to have beer with.
But it was out here on the highway.
You had to have a car to get out there.
And Brian, you could ride the bus into Brian.
Other than that.
Now after the war, I know, went out toward Snook and immediately crossed the river with a place with the nickname Whiskey Bridge.
Whiskey Bridge, that's right.
Yeah, we had that too.
We didn't name it that.
I know what you're talking about.
Did an Aggie ever bring some whiskey brack to the dorm?
They did, but I never witnessed it.
Isn't that funny?
I never, in my dorm, the guys I ran with never.
All right, you mentioned smoking.
About how many, about what percentage of cadets smoked?
It wasn't a big percent.
I would say the ones I knew, in fact my roommate Bobby Woodham smoked.
And I wouldn't, you know, we had a discussion about smoking in the room.
I would say ten percent.
That's all?
That's all.
And they're smoking cigarettes?
Cigarettes, but a lot of them were tobacco chewers.
They chewed tobacco then.
No snuff?
No snuff.
Did some of them roll their own?
They did.
Yeah, I guess a few of them did.
What about pipes?
Bullderm.
Not many pipes.
Was it legal for them to smoke in the dorm?
There was no ordinance on it.
There was no rules.
It was just consideration.
But I don't recall smoking in a dorm, now that you mention it.
Had you and your buddies even heard the words that we now hear about drugs?
Did you even know what?
Didn't know what it was about.
Marijuana?
Never heard of it.
Cocaine?
Didn't know what that's all about.
Let's see.
What about card games in the dorms?
Oh, yeah.
I never was a card player, but that went on.
I mean some of them would play all night.
Poker?
Poker.
Oh yeah, that went on.
Dominoes?
Not too much.
Just poker.
Maybe at the Y they played dominoes.
Was some of the poker for money?
Oh yeah, yeah.
Let's see, we did dates and you didn't go to summer school here, ever?
One semester.
Oh, you did?
I'm trying to remember.
One six-week course I went here.
How was that different?
It wasn't much different, just less students, more time for recreation, more time for handball.
Me and Manny Smith.
And were there, there were some girls then?
Oh yeah.
There were girls then.
But not much, not much.
Went in and mingling and socializing.
Because normally the guy would come to summer school.
He had an objective he wanted to get out of the way.
What did you and your friends do for recreation, for fun?
Not much.
Well, Saturday night, I take it back, we would go to Bryan.

He'd go to the Dixie Cafe and have a sandwich or something or go to the Wooden Dairy Queen Inn, it was another name, have an ice cream cone and walk around Bryan and just stand on the corner and have a bowl session and about 11 o'clock come on back.
And did you hitchhike down there?
I had a bus running.
Oh, okay.
Where was the bus?
At the Northgate?
Northgate.
And I'm always closing the Northgate.
The upperclassman says, too cold, go close the Northgate.
That's where Lipscomb Drugstore was.
We used to go there a lot.
hang around the drug store.
Did they have a soda fountain?
Oh yes, a soda fountain.
What else was there at Northgate?
Well, Harlech Boots Shop was there, Lucchese was there, Campus Clothing Store was there, a few hamburger joints.
Campus Theater.
Campus Theater, oh yeah.
But it's not like it is now.
Now, Lewpott was there.
Did you ever get a loan from old Army Lew?
No, sir.
I never did.
He said he never had a student that failed to pay off his loan.
I believe it.
That they were all honest.
Let's see, do you remember when you bought your senior ring?
I sure do.
Describe that please.
I had accumulated enough money to buy my ring.
How much did it cost?
I want to say $90.
I don't have any idea.
I want to say $90.
I think they're $300 or $400 now.
And my boots were about $100.
I still got my boots.
But when I got my Aggie ring,
I put that thing on and I was so proud.
I took it home and showed it to Papa and Mama and they were so proud.
Of course, I already had two of them, Pete and Jimmy.
But my boots.
Wait, let's stay with the ring.
Have you ever lost your ring?
No, sir.
Have you had any good ring stories?
I sure do.
Please share some of those.
One of the finest ring stories
happened to me during the Battle of the Bulge.
On the third day, we were fighting the Germans.
We were trying to push them out, trying to straighten the line out.
I was a forward observer with the infantry, and I was going to move from one OP across the field to another OP, which I thought would give me a better line of sight.
And as I got halfway, the Germans counterattacked with artillery and I hit the ground.
And I'm laying flat on my face
on the ground with my arms outstretched.
Next thing I knew somebody had thrown his arm on top of my arm and I looked at it and he had an Aggie ring on.
And I looked up and there was a colonel, Lieutenant Colonel.
I said, Colonel, my name's Coconose, Mike Coconose.
Lieutenant Kokonos, you got a brother named Pete?"
I said, yes sir, I sure do.
He and I are classmates, good friends, we had a lot of classes together.
I said, Colonel, get us out of here.
He said, I wish I could, I'd leave myself.
But we sat and chatted for a few minutes and
He was with the 94th Division.
His name was Colonel Berry.
And he was on his way back to his battalion when he saw me laying on the ground.
And he saw my ring, so he says, I thought I'd have some fun and throw my arm on top of your ring.
And I saw him about two years, three years after the
The war here at A&M at a football game, he had a heart attack after that and died.
But that was quite a story.
Oh, that's special.
Any other Ring stories?
Not really, except for that.
I don't believe I could top that.
Why are Aggie Rings so special and so treasured?
It stands for a great institution.
That's one of the reasons I love the ring.
And I look at it, mine's being worn down now because I never take it off except maybe play handball.
But it's special because it stands for a great college, great people, and your comrades, your classmates.
That's what it stands for.
Now, you mentioned this comrade.
What is it that builds that feeling of togetherness?
What is it that makes Aggies so proud?
They're proud because, first, they want to get an education.
Secondly, when they come up here, and when I came up here, we all put on the same uniform together.
We look alike.
There's no difference.
And I use Bum Bright as a perfect example.
Bum Bright who?
You've got the same khaki shirt I've got on, same brown shoes I have.
And that way it equalizes everybody.
And everybody shares the same relationship here at A&M.
Heartaches or troubles or things or happiness that no other college has.
It's unique.
It's unique here.
And are there certain experiences or events that are key to building that unity?
Well the bonfire is a deal.
We had bonfires.
Yale practice, silver taps.
Commencements?
Commencements.
Football games?
Football games, standing up at every people.
The public are amazed that we never sit down.
Even in those days, go back to Beaumont and say you guys never sit down.
As long as that team's out on the field we never sit down.
We're ready to go in if they need us.
And we don't, at that time we didn't worry about the academic standing of A&M.
We knew it was a good school.
And we wanted to make it better.
And this cohesion we had as a student body, I think, helped the former student association find a sink that happened to A&M.
In general, describe the student body when you were here.
Where were they from?
What kind of families?
What kind of background?
And what kind of attitudes?
I smile when you say that, because I never heard of Dobine.
I never heard of Snook.
Round Rock, I never heard of all these places.
Linden, I never heard of Linden.
And all these guys coming in from different parts of the state of Texas.
And you know what?
They're just like me.
That was so nice.
They're no different than I am.
And he might have been bigger and taller or shorter and fatter.
But his attitude was the same as mine.
Wasn't getting an education.
And I never heard of Hearn.
I never heard of Caldwell.
So that's what makes A&M so unique.
All right, senior boots.
Where'd you buy them?
Luke Casey.
Still got them.
Got them underneath my clothes rack when I come in from the office.
I put my coat in there.
There's my boots.
And I keep them there because my grandchildren come in.
I have 19 of them.
And they come in, and they're now 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12 years old.
They want to put them on and walk through the house.
So I let them walk through the house with my spurs and everything.
How did you feel when you first put those boots on?
Oh, top of the world.
They did.
Had a waist about 32 inches.
Good shape, felt good, put on them boots, boot britches.
Now, were you yet going steady with this young lady?
No, that finally went by the waist.
I really never went steady with any girl.
Okay, so your future wife, you had not?
Oh, no.
I met her at church, and that's how we got married.
Let's see, final review.
Did y'all... Grig Feely, not the owner of Drill Field.
Describe that, please.
Oh, he just, well, made several of them, as you know, but my final review...
This spring of 40?
And it was kind of sad.
because we knew everybody was going to go a different direction.
Normally, when you graduate from college, you keep in touch with your classmates, but in this situation, we knew we were all going different directions and didn't know when we'd see each other again.
It was very touching.
Do you remember who the reviewing officer was?
I don't remember.
The commandant here was Colonel Welty.
He was tough.
Ooh, he was tough.
Who came up for your final review and commencement from your family?
I don't think anybody come up.
Mom and dad didn't come?
Mama couldn't come up.
Papa couldn't come up.
They couldn't come up.
First place didn't have the transportation to get them up here.
And my brother Pete was in Bay City.
and he couldn't come.
Jimmy was on his way to Australia and Andrew was already here.
Now did you already have orders to report for active duty?
Not at that time.
Not at that time?
I had a unique situation.
I applied to medical school and the military told me here, Colonel Welty said, okay, you will delay your entry until you're here from medical school in May.
My class left in December, I mean the first part of February, 43.
They went en masse to OCS.
Well, May came and I wasn't accepted to medical school, so I was told that I would have to go to the Army, and I said, okay.
I said, I'll go to OCS like my classmates.
They did not allow that for me.
I had to go to basic training.
Oh.
Fourteen weeks.
Oh.
Colonel Welch would not turn loose my papers.
He went, of course, I didn't go in February.
I said, well, sir, you told me.
You're the one that told me I could delay.
Well, I made a mistake or something.
OK.
So I was called in and went to basic training.
then went to OCS.
I went with, I went to OCS with a class of 44 and 45.
They were called up, sent back to A&M, then went to, so it was all that.
Now this is Fort Sill?
Fort Sill, Oklahoma.
I went to OCS there.
In the summer of 43?
43, that's right.
As you... Incidentally, Fort Sill
Put me in the Hall of Fame.
They have a Hall of Fame for their officers.
Very good.
Because I went in as a basic trainee and come out as a general.
They like that.
As you look back, what did you learn here that's been important and significant, important in your life?
What did A&M teach you?
I never really asked that particular question, but A&M, I'll start off by saying without A&M, I don't know where I'd be.
I had no idea.
But A&M set me in the right direction of what I wanted to do and how to do it in a dedicated, honest, with integrity
way of doing things in life.
And that's what A&M, to me, set me on that course.

I could have been a politician, I could have been a vet, I could have been a doctor, I could have been an engineer, I could have been anything, but it told me this is how you do it and do it in the right way.
had that with Papa and Mama at home.
Discipline, honesty.
But this reinforced it.
This reinforced it, that's correct.
And how was that done and what methods were those values perpetuated here?
Well, the funny thing is I moved up
from sophomore to junior-senior, I counseled a lot of freshmen in my battery.
And I watched them and I could see they were being troubled by certain things and I would visit with them.
And A&M helped me to counsel with them, and A&M helped me to try to help them.
Actually, you can't really put your finger on what A&M does for you.
Just do it.
Did you become an officer in the Corps?
Yes, I was a second lieutenant on H Battery.
And what were your responsibilities there?
Well, to just work with the battery personnel, counseling.
That's probably the biggest one.
And I'm trying to remember some direct duties I had, but I just
I was an H battery officer.

As you look back over those years, if all the people that had been helpful to you were available today for you personally to express your appreciation to them, to whom would you most want to say words of appreciation and why?
Your A&M years.
Talking about cadets, or are you talking about anybody?
Anybody.
Cadets, teachers, advisers.
Well I think one of the dominating persons in my life was Barney Corot, my basketball coach.
Really liked him.
And Colonel Elwood.
What did you learn from those people?
I learned to do the best job I was possibly I could do.
That's what I learned from Corot.
As short as I was in basketball, he gave me the opportunity to compete against the tall guys, the best guys, and stuff like that.
And Colonel Elwood
instilled in me the military discipline that I needed to carry on in the war and in my military career along with that.
Who else?
I'm just, oh, there were so many guys that, there were really...
Some teachers, some friends?
Teachers, well, Dr. Hick felt, I mentioned his name before, but after that it became, I realized everything fell on me.
as an individual that I better not depend on anybody, but I could go get counseling if I needed it.
If you could be a consultant to A&M today, to the leadership, what advice would you give them about A&M's future?
What would you advise them to do in the future?
to make A&M become whatever it is you think it ought to be.
That's a very challenging statement you're making.
I think the management, and that's President Boyne and them and the board, need to really get down in touch with the former students more.
I think the student body
is okay.
